    "Midodrine is hepatically metabolized to its active metabolite desglymidodrine; in cirrhosis, metabolism may be impaired, potentially prolonging its effect and requiring lower starting doses in some patients.",
    "Common side effects of midodrine in cirrhosis include piloerection (goosebumps) in 10-15%, scalp tingling (5-10%), urinary urgency/retention (5-10%), and supine hypertension (10-15%).",
