    "Midodrine does not worsen portal hypertension or precipitate variceal bleeding; the arterial constriction is primarily systemic rather than splanchnic, and portal pressure is not significantly affected.",
    "In a meta-analysis of midodrine use in cirrhosis, the drug showed consistent improvement in MAP, renal blood flow, urine output, and sodium excretion across multiple small trials.",
    "Midodrine is a reasonable first-line pharmacological option for symptomatic orthostatic hypotension in compensated cirrhosis where the standard salt/fluid loading approach is contraindicated by ascites.",
    # Post-TIPS hemodynamic changes (116-130)
    "TIPS immediately reduces portal pressure by creating a low-resistance channel between the portal and hepatic veins; portal pressure gradient typically falls from 15-20 mmHg to 8-12 mmHg.",
    "The immediate increase in cardiac preload after TIPS (from redirected portal blood into the systemic circulation) causes a transient rise in cardiac output of 20-30% within the first 24-48 hours.",
    "Central venous pressure rises after TIPS placement; in patients with subclinical cirrhotic cardiomyopathy, this preload increase can unmask heart failure within the first week.",
    "Right heart catheterization or echocardiographic assessment before TIPS identifies patients at risk for post-TIPS cardiac decompensation; a pulmonary artery wedge pressure above 15 mmHg predicts heart failure.",
    "Systemic vascular resistance initially decreases further after TIPS (paradoxically) because of increased venous return triggering ANP release and further neurohormonal modulation.",
    "Over weeks to months after TIPS, systemic vascular resistance increases as the hyperdynamic state partially normalizes; MAP typically improves by 5-10 mmHg by 3-6 months post-TIPS.",
    "Renal blood flow improves after TIPS due to increased EABV and decreased RAAS activation; creatinine clearance improves by 25-40% in most patients, improving diuretic responsiveness.",
